1
00:00:05,577 --> 00:00:11,180
But I remember once asking
a senior godsister of mine,

2
00:00:11,180 --> 00:00:13,719
many years ago when I first joined
in New York,

3
00:00:13,796 --> 00:00:19,977
and discussing Bhagavad-gītā,
she’s a dear disciple of Srila Prabhupād.

4
00:00:20,655 --> 00:00:23,108
[Me Means Me]

5
00:00:23,771 --> 00:00:27,087
And, in the śloka 
where it would say,

6
00:00:27,087 --> 00:00:31,576
“Man-manā bhava mad-bhakto
mad-yājī māḿ namaskuru” (Bg: 9.34),

7
00:00:31,633 --> 00:00:37,962
or “Sarva-dharmān parityajya
mām ekaḿ śaraṇaḿ vraja” (Bg: 18.66),

8
00:00:37,962 --> 00:00:45,173
we were having a discussion about
how we know that ‘mām’ means Kṛṣṇa.

9
00:00:45,173 --> 00:00:50,394
And I was at the Kolkata Book Fair,
some years back

10
00:00:51,778 --> 00:00:55,618
—which is a huge international
book fair, actually—

11
00:00:55,618 --> 00:01:02,007
and I saw the Bhagavad-gītā
at one book stand,

12
00:01:02,007 --> 00:01:05,440
of, I believe
it was Dr. Radhakrishnan,

13
00:01:05,044 --> 00:01:09,758
he used to be
the former President of India,

14
00:01:09,758 --> 00:01:13,260
and Prabhupā
used to rail against

15
00:01:13,260 --> 00:01:18,317
some of the things that he would say,
in his purports.

16
00:01:18,317 --> 00:01:21,115
So I thought, 
“I just want to see”,

17
00:01:21,115 --> 00:01:24,345
’cause there’s this one thing
Prabhubād said that he said,

18
00:01:24,345 --> 00:01:27,683
and I wanted to see,
is that exactly how he said it?

19
00:01:27,683 --> 00:01:30,970
And it was like, 
practically to the word.

20
00:01:30,970 --> 00:01:35,347
Then I could understand why
it made Prabhupād so livid,

21
00:01:35,347 --> 00:01:39,354
he said, “In the man-manā bhava
mad-bhakto section,

22
00:01:39,354 --> 00:01:41,556
where Kṛṣṇa is saying, 
‘Think of me, become my devotee,

23
00:01:41,556 --> 00:01:43,731
give up everything, 
surrender unto me’”,

24
00:01:43,731 --> 00:01:50,354
his explanation, the tātparya,
the meaning, he says

25
00:01:50,399 --> 00:01:58,506
“It is not to the person, Kṛṣṇa, to whom
we are to give ourselves up to, utterly,

26
00:01:58,506 --> 00:02:03,850
but the unborn, impersonal,
who’s speaking through Kṛṣṇa.”

27
00:02:03,850 --> 00:02:06,825
Those are his exact words,

28
00:02:06,825 --> 00:02:13,448
and that would just make Prabhupād
furious, to hear those things.

29
00:02:13,755 --> 00:02:16,045
Right where Kṛṣṇa’s saying,
“Surrender to Me”,

30
00:02:16,075 --> 00:02:21,573
he’s saying, “It’s not … when He says
‘Me’ He doesn’t mean Himself,

31
00:02:21,573 --> 00:02:25,614
He means the unborn, impersonal,
that’s speaking through Him,

32
00:02:25,614 --> 00:02:29,132
who’s also speaking through you,
and me.”

33
00:02:29,132 --> 00:02:36,860
Like they would say, “If God is everywhere,
why do you have to go to the temple?”

34
00:02:36,860 --> 00:02:40,608
and Prabhupād said, “So you mean,
He’s not in the temple?

35
00:02:40,608 --> 00:02:47,141
He’s everywhere but the temple …
is that what you mean to say?”

36
00:02:47,556 --> 00:02:52,067
So, it reminded me again, 
in the temple,

37
00:02:52,067 --> 00:02:57,746
where Kṛṣṇa was living,
that some Indian man came by,

38
00:02:57,746 --> 00:03:01,089
and he had some appreciation
for the Sanskrit language,

39
00:03:01,089 --> 00:03:05,193
and we started talking about
the word “lotus”.

40
00:03:05,285 --> 00:03:06,956
“Ambhoja”

41
00:03:07,002 --> 00:03:08,138
“Padma”

42
00:03:08,154 --> 00:03:09,828
“Kamala”

43
00:03:09,875 --> 00:03:12,222
“Paṇkaja”

44
00:03:12,222 --> 00:03:14,956
What are other words for lotus …

45
00:03:14,986 --> 00:03:17,318
“Aravinda”

46
00:03:18,948 --> 00:03:21,884
“Nalina”

47
00:03:24,622 --> 00:03:27,020
And he was kind of ecstatic, like,

48
00:03:27,020 --> 00:03:29,449
“Oh, it’s just so wonderful,
the Sanskrit language”,

49
00:03:29,449 --> 00:03:33,438
and I said, “Yeah, and each time
some word is used,

50
00:03:33,438 --> 00:03:37,411
it’s not arbitrary 
or just poetic licence.

51
00:03:37,411 --> 00:03:44,976
But, very often,
the word that’s been selected,

52
00:03:47,129 --> 00:03:52,864
because of a precise accurate representation,
a particular thing is said.”

53
00:03:53,171 --> 00:03:57,891
And I wasn’t trying to start a fight
with him or anything, or just be smart,

54
00:03:57,891 --> 00:04:00,657
but I just said, like, 
it just came to my mind,

55
00:04:00,657 --> 00:04:04,058
that old conversation I had
with my godsister twenty years before;

56
00:04:04,058 --> 00:04:08,880
I said, “Like when Kṛṣṇa says
‘Sarva-dharmān, mām’, surrender to me.”

57
00:04:08,880 --> 00:04:10,598
It’s so simple.

58
00:04:10,598 --> 00:04:15,739
And that man—we’d just went through
a dozen meanings, vocabulary, of lotus—

59
00:04:15,739 --> 00:04:19,081
and I said, “When he says,
‘Sarva-dharmān’, surrender to me”,

60
00:04:19,081 --> 00:04:24,340
he goes, “Oh, I don’t know
so many things!”

61
00:04:24,340 --> 00:04:25,812
And I thought, 
“Oh really, you know

62
00:04:25,812 --> 00:04:31,147
twelve different words, substitute
for lotus, but where it says

63
00:04:31,147 --> 00:04:35,821
‘mām’, me … that,
‘I don’t know so many things.’”

64
00:04:35,821 --> 00:04:42,675
So, what does Kṛṣṇa say about that
In Bhagavad-gītā?

65
00:04:42,889 --> 00:04:49,402
“Avajānanti māṁ mūḍhā
mānuṣīṁ tanum āśritam

66
00:04:49,402 --> 00:04:53,791
paraṁ bhāvam ajānanto
mama bhūta-maheśvaram” (Bg: 9.11).

67
00:04:53,791 --> 00:05:01,394
“People who think I’m just a man,
talking here on a chariot to my friend,

68
00:05:01,394 --> 00:05:05,277
what are they?
Asses, “mudha”.

69
00:05:05,277 --> 00:05:08,746
“Na māḿ duṣkṛtino mūḍhāḥ
prapadyante narādhamāḥ” (Bg: 7.15);

70
00:05:08,746 --> 00:05:13,412
“And those people
they never surrender to Me.”

71
00:05:13,412 --> 00:05:14,676
Why?

72
00:05:14,676 --> 00:05:17,842
“Icchā-dveṣa-samutthena
dvandva-mohena bhārata” (Bg: 7.27);

73
00:05:17,842 --> 00:05:19,972
“They’re envious of Me.”

74
00:05:19,972 --> 00:05:22,040
So it’s one thing
for them to say

75
00:05:22,040 --> 00:05:26,477
they can’t imagine that the original
source of everything is personal,

76
00:05:26,477 --> 00:05:28,809
the Personality of Godhead,

77
00:05:28,809 --> 00:05:35,009
but really if you dig a little deeper,
it’s that, if it’s true that it’s a person,

78
00:05:35,009 --> 00:05:37,811
then what will your relationship be?

79
00:05:37,811 --> 00:05:39,707
One of equals?

80
00:05:39,707 --> 00:05:44,630
How many universes
did you create, recently?

81
00:05:45,338 --> 00:05:48,876
Someone could say,
“Well, one, a long time ago …

82
00:05:48,876 --> 00:05:52,076
it’s been downhill since then.”

83
00:05:52,076 --> 00:05:56,647
So, “Ahaḿ sarvasya prabhavo
mattaḥ sarvaḿ pravartate” (Bg: 10.8),

84
00:05:56,647 --> 00:06:02,324
Kṛṣṇa’s saying, “I’m the source of everything.
Everything comes from Me.”

85
00:06:02,324 --> 00:06:05,564
So whether it’s the Brahman conception,
Paramātmā, Bhagavān,

86
00:06:05,564 --> 00:06:08,774
and all varieties of Bhagavān,

87
00:06:08,774 --> 00:06:12,185
Lakṣmī–Narāyān, Sītā–Ram,

88
00:06:12,185 --> 00:06:14,931
Rukmiṇī and Dvārakānāth,

89
00:06:14,931 --> 00:06:17,558
Mathurānāth,

90
00:06:18,788 --> 00:06:21,419
Vrajendra-nandan …

